<methodology slug="business-model-research">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>research</group>
    <domain>researcher</domain>
    <summary>Systematic analysis of how business creates, delivers, and captures value via Business Model Canvas plus P10/P50/P90 unit economics and stress tests..</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>business-model</tag>
      <tag>unit-economics</tag>
      <tag>ltv</tag>
      <tag>cac</tag>
      <tag>pricing</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Business Model Research</title>

    <summary>Systematic analysis of how a business will create, deliver, and capture value, structured as a Business Model Canvas (9 blocks) plus P10/P50/P90 unit economics (CAC, LTV, LTV:CAC, payback period) and 5 stress tests. Every assumption is tagged Hard (sourced) or Soft (founder estimate); LTV must never use a lifetime of more than 60 months.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Entrepreneurs build products without viable business models — "we'll figure out monetization later" is the #1 cause of post-PMF collapse. A Canvas alone is theater without unit economics; unit economics at a single point hide the P10 scenario that actually determines runway. The P10 verdict is the only one that matters for fundraising and hiring decisions.</p>
      <p>Garbage-in churn: agents accept a 1%/month churn assumption from a blog post; LTV explodes 5x and the model looks viable when it is not. Single-point estimates (ARPU $29, churn 3%, CAC $50) hide ranges. Without P10/P50/P90 the LTV:CAC is theatre. Missing variable cost layer: gross margin treated as 80% by default (SaaS folklore) even when the product has 30% COGS (AI inference, payments, fulfillment).</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-spec phase: founder has a product idea but no defended monetization story.</item>
        <item>Pricing decision under uncertainty: ARPU/margin/churn assumptions must be modeled before a price page ships.</item>
        <item>Pivot review: existing product is missing LTV:CAC &gt;= 3:1 and the model itself may be broken.</item>
        <item>Investor memo/seed deck requiring "How we make money" section with stress tests.</item>
        <item>Multi-revenue-stream design: subscription + usage + marketplace fee blends.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Internal tools, OSS side-projects, hobby apps with no intent to monetize.</item>
        <item>Already-shipping products with 12+ months of real ARR data — use aarrr-pirate-metrics instead.</item>
        <item>Pure infrastructure libraries where revenue is a downstream consequence.</item>
        <item>Government/grant-funded work where the "customer" is a budget line.</item>
        <item>Two-sided marketplace pre-launch with zero supply — do network-effects first.</item>
        <item>Hardware/regulated products where margin is dictated by BOM + compliance, not chosen.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="business-model-canvas-and-revenue-archetypes">
      <p>Nine-block Business Model Canvas with Hard/Soft cell tagging and five revenue archetypes with variant tables and best-fit signals.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Populate all 9 Canvas blocks before naming any price; tag each cell Hard (sourced from a public filing, pricing page, or comparable company) or Soft (founder estimate).</statement>
        <rationale>Agents skip the Canvas and produce unit economics without understanding the cost structure. Hard/Soft tagging makes the assumptions ledger auditable and enables future re-runs to diff what changed.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>The nine Canvas blocks are: Customer Segments (who are the paying users? primary + secondary), Value Propositions (what value is delivered to each segment?), Channels (awareness, evaluation, purchase, delivery, after-sales), Customer Relationships (self-serve / assisted / automated; retention mechanisms), Revenue Streams (model type, price, estimated % of total revenue), Key Resources (physical, intellectual, human, financial), Key Activities (the 3 most critical activities for delivering value), Key Partners (what they provide, what they get in return), Cost Structure (fixed vs variable; cost-driven vs value-driven orientation).</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Shortlist exactly 2 of the 5 revenue archetypes that fit the value chain; reject the others on record with a one-line reason before running unit economics.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs default to SaaS subscription whenever the product is digital. Forcing an explicit rejection of the other four archetypes surfaces assumptions that would otherwise remain implicit.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Five revenue archetypes:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Subscription/SaaS: flat rate, tiered, per-seat, usage-based, freemium — best for ongoing value delivery, sticky products. Key metrics: MRR, churn, LTV, CAC.</item>
        <item>One-time purchase: digital product, software license, physical product — best for discrete value and impulse buys. Key metrics: units sold, revenue per product, repeat purchase rate.</item>
        <item>Transaction-based: percentage cut, flat fee per transaction, hybrid — best for marketplaces, payments, brokerage. Key metrics: GMV, take rate, transaction volume.</item>
        <item>Advertising: display, sponsored, affiliate — best for high-traffic content platforms. Key metrics: DAU, CPM, CTR, ad inventory fill rate.</item>
        <item>Marketplace/Commission: service, product, lead generation — best for matching problems with network effects. Key metrics: GMV, take rate, liquidity.</item>
      </list>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Assuming 20-30% take rate for a new marketplace.</description>
        <reason>Real successful marketplaces compress to 5-15% as suppliers gain leverage (Etsy 6.5%, Airbnb 14%, Upwork 10%). Agents assume high take rates because they pattern-match aspirational claims.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Using revenue as if it were profit in the Canvas Cost Structure block.</description>
        <reason>Gross margin must be sourced separately; AI-heavy products run 30-50% due to inference costs, not 80% SaaS folklore. Missing the Cost Structure block makes LTV:CAC unreliable.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Modeling freemium conversion at 15% without evidence.</description>
        <reason>Floor conversion is 2% (consumer) / 5% (B2B). Claims above these require an empirical citation or a Soft tag.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="unit-economics-and-stress-tests">
      <p>CAC/LTV/payback formulas, P10/P50/P90 scenario model, churn floor rules, and five stress tests that define model viability.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Always compute LTV with a lifetime cap of 60 months — the formula 1/churn explodes at low churn rates and produces fantasy LTVs.</statement>
        <rationale>1% monthly churn implies 100-month (8.3 year) average lifetime. SaaS products rarely sustain customers that long. Cap at 60 months unless backed by a 10-K showing 5-year cohorts.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Core formulas:</p>
      <list>
        <item>CAC = total marketing + sales spend / new customers acquired (use paid CAC for LTV:CAC, not blended)</item>
        <item>LTV = ARPU * gross_margin * min(1/churn, 60 months)</item>
        <item>LTV:CAC ratio target: 3:1 or higher. Below 1:1 = burning cash on acquisition. Below 3:1 = marginal at scale.</item>
        <item>Payback period = CAC / (ARPU * gross_margin). Target: &lt;12 months. &gt;24 months requires exceptional retention evidence.</item>
      </list>

      <rule>
        <statement>Run unit economics in three scenarios (P10 pessimistic, P50 base, P90 optimistic) before writing any verdict; the P10 verdict is the only one that matters for runway and hiring decisions.</statement>
        <rationale>Single-point LTV:CAC hides the distribution. Investors and operators need to know if the model survives a bad quarter (P10), not just a median one. Refusing to average ranges is a hard rule.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="P10/P50/P90 scenario analysis">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
P10: ARPU $20, churn 6%, CAC $80 → LTV $280, LTV:CAC 3.5:1, payback 20mo.
P50: ARPU $29, churn 3%, CAC $50 → LTV $773, LTV:CAC 15:1, payback 9mo.
P90: ARPU $38, churn 2%, CAC $35 → LTV $1267, LTV:CAC 36:1, payback 5mo.
Verdict based on P10: model survives at minimum threshold.
        ]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule>
        <statement>The model passes only if it survives all five stress tests at P50 and does not go below 1:1 LTV:CAC at P10.</statement>
        <rationale>A model that passes only 4 of 5 tests at P50 has a known failure mode that will materialize as the business scales. Documenting the failure mode is more valuable than optimistic forecasting.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Five stress tests that define model viability:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Scale: does unit economics hold at 10x, 100x customers? (Watch: marginal infrastructure costs, support load)</item>
        <item>Competition: what if prices drop 50%? (Check: can gross margin absorb a 50% ARPU cut?)</item>
        <item>Churn: what if monthly churn doubles? (Run: P10 with churn * 2 applied)</item>
        <item>CAC: what if acquisition costs rise 3x? (Check: channel saturation, Apple ATT, cookie deprecation)</item>
        <item>Time: how long until profitable at P50? (Calculate: break-even customer count = fixed costs / contribution margin)</item>
      </list>

      <rule>
        <statement>Refuse to compute LTV with monthly churn below 1% unless backed by a public 10-K — sub-1% churn is a unicorn claim requiring evidence.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents accept 0.5%/month churn from a blog post; LTV explodes 5x and the model looks viable when it is not. Baremetrics benchmarks show median SaaS monthly churn at 2-4%.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Model churn as cohort-variable, not flat — month-1 churn is 3-10x month-12 churn. Flat churn assumptions understate early-cohort losses.</statement>
        <rationale>New users churn at much higher rates than retained users. A flat 3%/month model dramatically underestimates first-month losses and overestimates LTV.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="business-model-agentic-pipeline">
      <p>Eight-step workflow, subagents, prompt patterns for build and validate passes, SDD integration, and agent gotchas.</p>

      <p>Eight-step pipeline:</p>
      <list>
        <item>1. Value chain map: agent diagrams Suppliers -&gt; Product -&gt; Customers with cost arrows; founder confirms before any price is named</item>
        <item>2. Revenue-model shortlist: pick 2 of 5 archetypes that fit the value chain; reject others on record</item>
        <item>3. Comparable harvesting: WebSearch 3-5 public competitors per shortlisted model; pull pricing pages, S-1/10-K if listed</item>
        <item>4. Canvas fill: populate all 9 blocks; mark each cell Hard/Soft</item>
        <item>5. Unit economics block: compute CAC, LTV, LTV:CAC, payback in P10/P50/P90</item>
        <item>6. Stress test: run 5 tests; model passes only if it survives all five at P50</item>
        <item>7. Verdict: one of {viable, viable-with-fixes, not-viable}; if not-viable, propose 2 alternative models and re-loop step 2</item>
        <item>8. Validation pass: peer agent re-reads against assumptions ledger and returns delta list</item>
      </list>

      <example type="good" title="Build prompt — step sequence enforced, Hard/Soft tagging required">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
You are a business-model analyst. Build a Business Model Canvas + unit
economics for: <product idea>. Constraints: <ICP, geo, stage>.
Steps: (1) map value chain, (2) shortlist 2 of 5 revenue archetypes,
(3) pull 3 public comparables per archetype, (4) fill Canvas with
H/S tags per cell, (5) compute CAC/LTV/payback in P10/P50/P90,
(6) run all 5 stress tests, (7) emit verdict.
Refuse to average ranges. Cite source URL + retrieval date for every
Hard cell. Output: markdown matching business-model-canvas.md sections.
        ]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Validate prompt — returns delta list, not a rewrite">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Validate this business model: <paste canvas + unit economics>.
Check: (1) is gross margin sourced or assumed? (2) does churn vary by
cohort age? (3) does LTV:CAC survive at P10? (4) are revenue streams
additive or substitutive? (5) is payback < 12 months at P50?
Return delta list, not rewrite.
        ]]></code>
      </example>

      <p>Recommended subagents:</p>
      <list>
        <item>faion-research-agent — orchestrator, mode business-model dispatches this methodology.</item>
        <item>faion-market-researcher-agent — declared in README front-matter; methodology-aware Canvas + unit-economics agent.</item>
        <item>faion-product-manager-agent — validates the verdict against product roadmap and pricing decisions.</item>
        <item>faion-domain-checker-agent — pairs once a name + model are chosen, before any price page is built.</item>
        <item>General web-research / WebSearch subagent — pulls competitor pricing pages, S-1 filings, earnings calls.</item>
      </list>

      <p>SDD integration points:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Output lives at .aidocs/product_docs/business-model.md; assumptions ledger at .aidocs/product_docs/business-model-assumptions.csv</item>
        <item>Reads SOM from market-research.md as the revenue ceiling; refuses to publish if year-3 forecast &gt; SOM</item>
        <item>roadmap.md MRR/ARR targets must reference a Canvas version; bumps require a new model run and a delta entry</item>
        <item>spec.md lists revenue-affecting requirements traced to a Canvas cell (Key Activities or Revenue Streams)</item>
      </list>

      <p>Agent gotchas in business model research:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Churn hallucination: model invents 2%/month "industry standard" — require a Baremetrics or ChartMogul benchmark URL or a 10-K citation.</item>
        <item>ARPU vs ARR confusion: monthly and annual numbers mixed in the same LTV calc — LTV is off by 12x and goes unnoticed.</item>
        <item>Confirmation bias: founder mentions "$10M ARR by year 3" — agent reverse-engineers customer count and price; pre-commit Canvas before sharing the target.</item>
        <item>Static churn: one churn number for 36 months; require cohort-variable modeling (month-1 churn is 3-10x month-12).</item>
        <item>Margin laziness: agent uses revenue as if it were profit; require a Cost Structure block before any LTV cell renders.</item>
        <item>Output drift: each rerun rewrites the entire Canvas; lock headings to business-model-canvas.md and only fill cells; version the file.</item>
        <item>Currency mixing: USD pricing pages, EUR comps, GBP local — normalize at retrieval, not at report time.</item>
        <item>Compounding fractions: freemium 5% × paid 80% retention × upgrade 20% produces false precision; round each to one sig fig.</item>
        <item>Take-rate fantasy: agent assumes 30% take on a marketplace because the founder hinted at high margin; cap at 15% unless there is a moat.</item>
        <item>"We will charge what competitors charge": agent copies competitor pricing without checking unit economics; rerun with own COGS + CAC.</item>
        <item>Static churn assumption: agent uses one churn number for all 36 months; cohort decay is 3–10x in month-1 vs month-12.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="tools-and-services-for-business-models">
      <p>CLI tools for business model research:</p>
      <list>
        <item>gh (GitHub CLI) — Pull competitor open-source repos for traction signal | brew install gh / cli.github.com</item>
        <item>crunchbase-api — Funding stage, headcount, founded year for comparables | data.crunchbase.com/docs</item>
        <item>sec-edgar (python-sec-edgar) — Public-company S-1/10-K — gold-standard ARPU, churn, CAC | github.com/jadchaar/sec-edgar-downloader</item>
        <item>simfin — Financial filings as parsed CSV (free tier) | simfin.com</item>
        <item>yfinance — Public market cap, revenue multiples for comparables | github.com/ranaroussi/yfinance</item>
        <item>pricing-page-scraper (Playwright recipe) — Snapshot competitor pricing tiers | playwright.dev</item>
        <item>wayback-machine (waybackpack) — Pin a pricing page on a specific date | github.com/jsvine/waybackpack</item>
        <item>numpy-financial — NPV, IRR, payback period calculators | pypi.org/project/numpy-financial</item>
        <item>csvkit + pandoc — Convert competitor pricing tables into the report template | csvkit.rtfd.io</item>
        <item>claude (Anthropic CLI) — Run agent prompts above in batch | docs.anthropic.com</item>
      </list>

      <p>Services and apps for business model agents:</p>
      <list>
        <item>SEC EDGAR (Public filings) — Yes, agent-friendly. Free API. Gold-standard for SaaS ARR, gross margin, churn.</item>
        <item>Crunchbase (Funding/competitor DB) — Yes, agent-friendly. REST API, key required. Stage + headcount for comps.</item>
        <item>PitchBook (Private market data) — Partial, agent-friendly. Enterprise API. Better than Crunchbase for late-stage.</item>
        <item>ChartMogul (SaaS metrics SaaS) — Yes, agent-friendly. REST API. Plug-in for own data; benchmark API exists.</item>
        <item>ProfitWell / Paddle (Subscription metrics) — Yes, agent-friendly. REST API. Industry benchmark medians (free tier).</item>
        <item>Stripe Atlas (Incorporation + payments) — N/A. Reference pricing for transactional model fees.</item>
        <item>Baremetrics Open Benchmarks (SaaS benchmarks) — Yes, agent-friendly. Public dataset. MRR/churn medians by ARPU band.</item>
        <item>OpenView SaaS Benchmarks (Annual report) — No, not agent-friendly. PDF. Cite for usage-based pricing share.</item>
        <item>OPEXEngine (OPEX benchmarks) — Paid. Cost-structure side of canvas.</item>
        <item>Apptopia / data.ai (Mobile app revenue) — Paid REST API. Consumer-app revenue estimates.</item>
        <item>App Annie / Sensor Tower (Same) — Paid. Use for one-time and freemium consumer apps.</item>
        <item>Strategyzer (Canvas tooling SaaS) — Partial, not agent-friendly. No public API. Reference template only.</item>
        <item>Stripe Sigma / Atlas data (Aggregated SaaS data) — Partial, not agent-friendly. Login. Take-rate baselines for transactional models.</item>
        <item>Google Sheets / Notion (Canvas + math host) — Yes, agent-friendly. APIs. Where the agent writes the editable copy.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices-for-business-models">
      <list>
        <item>Lock the value chain in one diagram before any price is named — agents skip this step and produce numbers without context.</item>
        <item>Refuse to compute LTV with monthly churn under 1% unless backed by a public 10-K — sub-1% churn is a unicorn claim.</item>
        <item>Always compute LTV with a churn floor (e.g. cap lifetime at 60 months) — the formula 1/churn explodes at low churn.</item>
        <item>Run unit economics in P10/P50/P90, not a single point — the verdict at P10 is the only one that matters for runway.</item>
        <item>Use gross margin from the comparable's 10-K, not "80% because SaaS" — AI-heavy products often run 30–50% due to inference cost.</item>
        <item>Distinguish CAC blended (all spend / all customers) from paid CAC (paid spend / paid customers); LTV:CAC must use paid CAC.</item>
        <item>For transactional models, model take-rate decay: marketplaces compress 1–2 points/year as suppliers gain leverage.</item>
        <item>For freemium, model conversion-rate floor at 2% (consumer) / 5% (B2B) — claims of 15% require evidence.</item>
        <item>Diversify revenue only if streams are non-substitutive (a community upsell on top of a course is good; two separate subscription tiers is one stream).</item>
        <item>Re-run the model every quarter against actuals; the assumption ledger surfaces which Soft cells are aging.</item>
        <item>Tag the model file as version: vN in front-matter and commit; pricing decisions reference the version, not the date.</item>
        <item>Cap Soft-cell compounding at 3 deep — 0.5 × 0.4 × 0.3 × 0.2 = 1.2% is a fantasy, not a forecast.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/business-model-canvas.md" purpose="Fillable 9-block canvas with Hard/Soft cell tagging."/>
      <template path="templates/unit-econ-scenarios.sh" purpose="P10/P50/P90 LTV:CAC and payback from arpu/margin/churn/cac args."/>
    </templates>

